"Jang C.J., Park J., Park T., Yoo S.","Response of the ocean mixed layer depth to global warming and its impact on primary production: A case for the North Pacific Ocean",2011,"ICES Journal of Marine Science","68","6",,"996","1007",,,10.1093/icesjms/fsr064,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-79959494013&partnerID=40&md5=6e4c171b2704aa78c9acc6a51c48576e","Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sa-dong, Ansan, Gyeonggi-do, 426-170, South Korea","Jang, C.J., Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sa-dong, Ansan, Gyeonggi-do, 426-170, South Korea; Park, J., Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sa-dong, Ansan, Gyeonggi-do, 426-170, South Korea; Park, T., Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sa-dong, Ansan, Gyeonggi-do, 426-170, South Korea; Yoo, S., Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sa-dong, Ansan, Gyeonggi-do, 426-170, South Korea","This study investigates changes in the mixed layer depth (MLD) in the North Pacific Ocean in response to global warming and their impact on primary production by comparing outputs from 11 models of the coupled model intercomparison projects phase 3. The MLD in the 21st century decreases in most regions of the North Pacific, whereas the spatial pattern of the MLD is nearly unchanged. The overall shoaling results in part from intensified upper-ocean stratification caused by both surface warming and freshening. A significant MLD decrease (>30 m) is found in the Kuroshio extension (KE), which is predominantly driven by reduced surface cooling, caused by weakening of wind. Associated with the mixed layer shoaling in the KE, the primary production component resulting from seasonal vertical mixing will be reduced by 10.740.3 (ranges of medians from 11 models) via decreased nitrate fluxes from below it. Spring blooms in most models are projected to initiate earlier in the KE by 013 d (ranges of medians from 11 models). Despite the overall trends, the magnitude of changes in primary production and timing of spring blooms are quite different depending on models and latitudes. © 2011 International Council for the Exploration of the Sea.","coupled models; global warming; mixed layer depth; North Pacific Ocean; primary production","cooling; global warming; latitude; magnitude; mixed layer; numerical model; physiological response; primary production; twenty first century; Kuroshio Extension; Pacific Ocean",,,,,,"Baker, K.S., Frouin, R., Relation between photosynthetically available radiation and total insolation at the ocean surface under clear skies (1987) Limnology and Oceanography, 32, pp. 1370-1377; Breitbarth, E., Oschlies, A., LaRoche, J., Physiological constraints on the global distribution of Trichodesmium - Effect of temperature on diazotrophy (2007) Biogeosciences, 4 (1), pp. 53-61; Capone, D.G., Burns, A.J., Montoya, J.P., Subramaniam, A., Mahaffey, C., Gunderson, T., Michaels, A.F., Nitrogen fixation by Trichodesmium spp.: An important source of new nitrogen to the tropical and subtropical North Atlantic Ocean (2005) Global Biogeochemical Cycles, 19, pp. GB2024. , doi:10.1029/ 2004GB002331; Capone, D.G., Zehr, J.P., Paerl, H.W., Bergman, B., Carpenter, E.J., Trichodesmium, a globally significant marine cyanobacter-ium (1997) Science, 276, pp. 1221-1229; Carpenter, E.J., Subramaniam, A., Capone, D.G., Biomass and primary productivity of the cyanobacterium Trichodesmium spp. in the tropical N Atlantic ocean (2004) Deep-Sea Research Part I: Oceanographic Research Papers, 51 (2), pp. 173-203. , DOI 10.1016/j.dsr.2003.10.006; Collins, W.D., Bitz, C.M., Blackmon, M.L., Bonan, G.B., Bretherton, C.S., Carton, J.A., Chang, P., Smith, R.D., The Community Climate System Model version 3 (CCSM3) (2006) Journal of Climate, 19 (11), pp. 2122-2143. , DOI 10.1175/JCLI3761.1; De Boyer Montégut, C., Madec, G., Fischer, A.S., Lazar, A., Iudicone, D., Mixed layer depth over the global ocean: An examination of profile data and a pro